<BaseLayout title="Assessment" mode="teacher" active="assessment" description="Assessment guidance for the Macbeth Literary Heritage coursework: the AO1, AO2 and AO4 split, a paraphrased quality ladder, the comment-only marking workflow across three drafts, examiner pitfalls, and the integrity position.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">Edexcel International GCSE English Literature &middot; Component 3: Literary Heritage</p>
      <h1>Assessment</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        One essay on Macbeth, marked out of 30, with the three assessment objectives weighted equally. Here
        is the split in practical terms, a paraphrased quality ladder, the marking workflow across the three
        drafts, the examiner pitfalls to teach against, and the integrity position that shapes the whole
        unit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">

      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">The AO split</h2>
      <p>
        The essay is marked out of 30, divided equally across three objectives at ten marks each. To reach
        the top, a response must serve all three, and not lean on the one the student finds easiest.
      </p>
      <ul class="tick">
        <li><strong>AO1 (10 marks):</strong> close knowledge and understanding of the play, a critical style, and informed personal engagement. In practice: an argued reading in the student&rsquo;s own voice, accurate about plot and character, that answers the actual question rather than the topic.</li>
        <li><strong>AO2 (10 marks):</strong> analysis of the language, form and structure Shakespeare uses to make meaning and effect. In practice: short quotations worked closely, and form treated as theatre, soliloquy, staging, dramatic irony, verse and prose, and what is played on stage against what is kept off it.</li>
        <li><strong>AO4 (10 marks):</strong> the relationship between the play and its contexts. In practice: a full third of the mark, so context is embedded in topic sentences and looped back to in the analysis, never parked in a paragraph of its own.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The quality ladder, paraphrased</h2>
      <p class="small">Paraphrased for planning only. Always mark against the current published grid.</p>
      <table class="sow">
        <thead><tr><th>Band</th><th>What it looks like in a Macbeth essay</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Bottom</strong></td><td>Largely retelling: the student narrates what happens, with quotations dropped in and little worked analysis; context is thin or absent, and the question is answered only in passing.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Middle</strong></td><td>Sound, relevant analysis: a clear line of argument, relevant close reading of language, form or structure, appropriate critical style, and context that is present and relevant if not always fully integrated.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Top</strong></td><td>Assured and perceptive: discriminating evidence chosen from across the whole play, cohesive evaluation rather than description, the theatrical dimension and the context woven throughout, an essay with ideas of its own.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        The three bands describe direction of travel, not exact marks. Place a response by best fit and then
        confirm the mark against the current published grid from Pearson: the descriptors here are a
        teaching shorthand, not a substitute for it.
      </p>

      <h2>The marking workflow, comment-only</h2>
      <p>
        The work is submitted in three stages, a first draft, a second draft and a final submission, with
        feedback on the first two that the student is expected to act on carefully. Marking is
        <strong>comment-only</strong>: no rewriting of passages, no line-by-line correction that turns the
        redraft into the teacher&rsquo;s work. Comment at the level of pattern, and let the student do the
        redrafting.
      </p>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li><strong>First draft.</strong> Read three times, quickly: once for argument (is there a thesis, or a run of observations?), once for method (is each device pushed to its effect?), and once for evidence range and context (across the play, and embedded, not bolted on?). Feed back on the two or three patterns that would most raise the essay.</li>
        <li><strong>Second draft.</strong> Check the earlier feedback was acted on, then comment on the next tier of issues. Keep steering the student rather than steering the pen.</li>
        <li><strong>Final submission.</strong> Confirm the formatting rules are met and the declaration is signed; the mark is settled here against the published grid.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Deliver feedback through the shared marking codes so students can decode and act on it independently:
        Sp, Gr, Exp, Vg, the missing-word caret, P, C, SWA (single-word analysis, zoom in) and the
        double-slash for a missing paragraph break. The full set is taught in
        <a href="/teachers/lessons/#l5">Lesson 5</a>. Comments are removed by the student before each
        resubmission.
      </p>

      <h2>Examiner pitfalls to teach against</h2>
      <ul class="tick">
        <li><strong>Device-spotting.</strong> Naming a technique is labelling, not analysis. Nothing is earned until the effect on the audience is explored.</li>
        <li><strong>Bolted-on context.</strong> A history paragraph with no return to the text. Context belongs in the topic sentence and the loop back.</li>
        <li><strong>Unbalanced objectives.</strong> Strong on language, silent on context, or the reverse. Each objective carries ten marks, so balance them within every paragraph.</li>
        <li><strong>Narrative retelling.</strong> Recounting the plot in place of an argument. Topic sentences should make a claim, not summarise.</li>
        <li><strong>Quotation without analysis.</strong> Evidence dropped in and left unworked. Quote briefly, then analyse the words themselves.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="box teach">
        <h3>Authentication and integrity</h3>
        <p>
          This is assessed coursework, so the authentication rules are firm. There is <strong>no AI
          marking</strong>: the teacher declares the work was completed without unacceptable assistance and
          that AI has not been used to mark it. There is <strong>no AI drafting or editing</strong> of the
          essay: the candidate declares the work is their own. Any sources and any artificial intelligence
          tools used must be referenced, and a false declaration is malpractice.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is why the site carries no automated feedback tool: an AI marker would sit exactly where the
          declarations say nothing automated should be. The site gives knowledge, method and worked
          guidance; the argument and the writing remain the student&rsquo;s own, which is the point of
          coursework. The <a href="/coursework/#integrity">integrity rules</a> are set out for students in
          plain language.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
